alz-Kreis, Saarland, Germany":"Erfweiler, Mandelbachtal, Saarpfalz-Kreis, Saarland, Germany","Erfweiler, Pirmasens, Rheinland-Pfalz, Deutschland":"Erfweiler, Pirmasens, Rhineland-Palatinate, Germany","Erfweiler, Mandelbachtal, Saar-Pfalz-Kreis, Saarland, Deutschland":"Erfweiler, Mandelbachtal, Saarpfalz-Kreis, Saarland, Germany","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Landorf","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: habitational name from any of numerous places in northwestern Germany named Handorf."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Paul","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Latin <i>Paulus</i>, a Roman family name, originally a nickname meaning ‘small’, used in the post-classical period as a given name. Pre-eminently this is the name of the saint who is generally regarded, with  St Peter , as co-founder of the Christian Church. Born in Tarsus, and originally named <i>Saul</i>, he was both a Roman citizen and a Jew, and at first found employment as a minor official persecuting Christians. He was converted to Christianity by a vision of Christ while on the road to Damascus, and thereafter undertook extensive missionary journeys, converting people, especially Gentiles, to Christianity all over the eastern Mediterranean. His preaching aroused considerable official hostility, and eventually he was beheaded at Rome in about   ad  65 . He is the author of the fourteen epistles to churches and individuals which form part of the New Testament. It has been in continuous use in the British Isles since the 16th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Paulus","meanings":["From Latin <i>Paulus</i>, a Roman family name, originally a nickname meaning ‘small’, used in the post-classical period as a given name. Pre-eminently this is the name of the saint who is generally regarded, with  St Peter , as co-founder of the Christian Church. Born in Tarsus, and originally named <i>Saul</i>, he was both a Roman citizen and a Jew, and at first found employment as a minor official persecuting Christians. He was converted to Christianity by a vision of Christ while on the road to Damascus, and thereafter undertook extensive missionary journeys, converting people, especially Gentiles, to Christianity all over the eastern Mediterranean. His preaching aroused considerable official hostility, and eventually he was beheaded at Rome in about   ad  65 . He is the author of the fourteen epistles to churches and individuals which form part of the New Testament. It has been in continuous use in the British Isles since the 16th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Paul Landorf was born in 1575, in Erfweiler, Pirmasens, Rhineland-Palatinate, Germany, his father, Matheis Landorf, was 21 and his mother, Agatha Schwarz, was 27. He married Susanna Hurth about 1600. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. His occupation is listed as ackerer  in Erfweiler, Mandelbachtal, Saarpfalz-Kreis, Saarland, Germany. He died in 1617, in his hometown, at the age of 42."},"et":{"1575–1617":"1575–1617","1577–Male":"1577–Surnud","1580–1635":"1580–1635","1580–1629":"1580–1629","1608–1694":"1608–1694","–1717":"–1717","1555–1608":"1555–1608","1548–1636":"1548–1636","ungefähr 1608":"1608","1580":"1580","1635":"1635","1555":"1555","1577":"1577","1575":"1575","um 1582":"umbes 1582","about 1600":"umbes 1600","1694":"1694","1608":"1608","1717":"1717","1629":"1629","1617":"1617","1636":"1636","1548":"1548","Erfweiler, Mandelbachtal, Saar-Pfalz-Kreis, Saarland, Germany":"Erfweiler, Mandelbachtal, Saarpfalz-Kreis, Saarland, Saksamaa","Erfweiler, Pirmasens, Rheinland-Pfalz, Deutschland":"Erfweiler, Landkreis Pirmasens, Rheinland-Pfalz, Saksamaa","Erfweiler, Mandelbachtal, Saar-Pfalz-Kreis, Saarland, Deutschland":"Erfweiler, Mandelbachtal, Saarpfalz-Kreis, Saarland, Saksamaa"},"fi":{"1575–1617":"1575–1617","1577–Male":"1577–Kuollut","1580–1635":"1580–16